#Make a table showing showing the mean, median, and standard deviaion of the BDI score at each visit.
pulse_data = read_sas("../data/public_pulse_data.sas7bdat") %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  gather(key = visit, value = bdi, bdiscore_bl:bdiscore_12m)

pulse_data %>%  
  group_by(visit) %>%
  summarize(mean_dbdi = mean(bdi), 
            median_bdi = median (bdi),
            sd_bdi = sd(bdi)) %>% 
  kable()
visit mean_dbdi median_bdi sd_bdi
bdiscore_01m 5.599608 4 6.562443
bdiscore_06m 5.586829 4 6.433842
bdiscore_12m 5.895855 4 7.183757
bdiscore_bl 7.707199 6 7.170690

1.3 box plot and violin plot

#Make box and violin plots 
#showing the distribution of BDI score at each visit. Comment on the distribution of BDI score.
ggplot(pulse_data, aes(x = visit, y = bdi )) + geom_boxplot() 

ggplot(pulse_data, aes(x = visit, y = bdi)) + 
  geom_violin(aes(fill = visit), color = "blue", alpha = .5) + 
  stat_summary(fun.y = median, geom = "point", color = "blue", size = 4)

##1.4

#Covert visit to a numeric variable, and make a “speghetti plot” of BDI score. That is, make a scatterplot showing each subject’s BDI score at each visit with lines connected repeated observations on the same subject. geom_path() will be useful. 
pulse_spe = pulse_data %>% 
  mutate(visit = as.factor(visit)) %>% 
  mutate(visit = as.numeric(factor(visit)))

p <- ggplot(data = pulse_spe, aes(x = visit, y = bdi, group = id, color = id))
## just plotting points (a.k.a., scatterplot)
p + geom_point()

## simple spaghetti plot
p + geom_path()

#Based on this plot, comment on the stability of BDI score within a person over time – do subjects with high BDI scores at baseline tend to have high BDI scores at 12 months?
  *Comment: Based on the plot, BDI score is relatively stable over time. Most subjects with high BDI scores at baseline tend to have relatively high BDI scores at 12 months.

#Make a table showing the mean hour of the day at which Pink Lady Apples and Coffee Ice Cream are ordered on each day of the week; format this table for human readers (i.e. produce a 2 x 7 table).
table_pinapple_coffee_ice_cream =ins_train_data %>% 
  select(product_name, order_dow, order_hour_of_day) %>%
  filter(product_name =="Pink Lady Apples"| product_name =="Coffee Ice Cream") %>% 
  group_by(product_name, order_dow) %>%
  summarise(mean_order_hour_day = mean(order_hour_of_day)) %>% 
  spread(key = product_name, value = mean_order_hour_day)

2.4 violin and ridge plot

  #Using violin and ridge plots, show the distribution of the order hour of the day for each department. Organize your plot according to the IQR of the order hour. Comment on the distributions, taking into account the which departments have the widest and narrowest IQRs.
  ins_train_data %>%
  select(department, order_hour_of_day) %>%
  group_by(department) %>% 
  mutate(IQR =IQR(order_hour_of_day)) %>%
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(department = forcats::fct_reorder(department, order_hour_of_day)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = department, y = order_hour_of_day)) + 
  geom_violin(aes( fill = "pink", color = "blue", alpha = .8)) + 
  ggtitle("Violin Plot of Order Hour") +
  stat_summary(fun.y = median, geom = "point", color = "blue", size = 1) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom", 
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)
       )

  ins_train_data %>%
 select(department, order_hour_of_day) %>%

  ungroup() %>%

  ggplot(aes(x = order_hour_of_day, y = department)) +

3.3

##Limiting your data to observations with snowfall values greater than 0 and less than 100 make a ridge plot showing the distribution of snowfall values for each year. Comment on the recorded snowfall values – are they clustered around specific entries? If so, why?
nyno_snow_data %>% 
  separate(date, into = c("year", "month", "day"), sep = "-") %>% 
   filter(snow < 100 & snow > 0) %>%   
 ggplot(aes(x =snow , y = year)) + 
  geom_density_ridges(scale = 1.5) +
  ggtitle("Ridge plot-snow each year")
## Picking joint bandwidth of 3.76

*From the plot, we can see that the snowfall values clustered around 10~30, 55 and 77. I think the reason is that the weather of each year is almost the same; thus, the distribution of snow fall follows almost the same pattern every year.

3.4

nyno_snow_data %>%
    filter(!is.na(tmax), !is.na(tmin)) %>% 
    separate(date, into = c("year", "month", "day"), sep = "-") %>%
    mutate(tmax = as.numeric(tmax), tmin = as.numeric(tmin)) %>% 
    mutate(month, month = factor(month, labels=month.name)) %>%
    group_by(year, month) %>%
    summarize(tmax = mean(tmax, na.rm = T), tmin = mean(tmin, na.rm = T)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = tmin, y = tmax, color = month, alpha = .5)) + 
        geom_point(aes(color = month), alpha = .5) + 
        geom_smooth(se = FALSE) + 
    labs(title = "The relation between tmax and tmin",
    x = "Minimum temperature",
    y = "Maximium temperature") +
        theme(legend.position = "bottom")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

*From the pattern, it shows that the relationship of tmax and tmin are similar, each month has its own range of tamx and tmin. Also, the month with hgih tamx tend to have high tmin.

3.5

nyno_snow_data %>% 
filter(!is.na(tmax), !is.na(tmin)) %>% 
    separate(date, into = c("year", "month", "day"), sep = "-") %>%
    mutate(tmax = as.numeric(tmax), tmin = as.numeric(tmin)) %>% 
    mutate(month, month = factor(month, labels=month.name)) %>%
    mutate(year = as.numeric(year), 
           month = as.numeric(month), 
           day = as.numeric(day)) %>% 
    group_by(id, month) %>%
    summarize(monthtmax = mean(tmax)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = month, y = monthtmax, group =  id, alpha = .5)) +
    geom_path() +
    theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
    labs(title = "Speghetti Plot of Mean Tmax for Each Station", x = "Month",
         y = "Monthly average maximum temperature") 

 *The average tmax curves for each station are clustered together. They almost all followed the same trends throughout the year.
 *Some stations have high tamx every month while some have low tamx every month.
